Let's consider a mathematical model of a regulatory agency. Suppose that the agency under the director's supervision has a set $A$ of $n$ actions that can be taken, and these actions can be represented as vectors in $\mathbb{R}^n$. Each action $a_i$ is associated with a cost $c_i \in \mathbb{R}$ for $i=1,2,...,n$. The director's task is to choose the combination of actions that minimizes the total cost, subject to some constraints.

The constraints are as follows: for each action $a_i$, there is a set $E_i$ of $m_i$ environmental conditions under which the action can be taken, and these conditions can be represented as vectors in $\mathbb{R}^{m_i}$. Each condition $e_{ij}$ is associated with a probability $p_{ij} \in [0,1]$ for $j=1,2,...,m_i$.

The director's problem can be modeled as the following optimization problem:

\[
\begin{aligned}
& \underset{a \in A}{\text{minimize}}
& & \sum_{i=1}^{n} c_i \cdot a_i \\
& \text{subject to}
& & \sum_{j=1}^{m_i} p_{ij} \cdot e_{ij} \leq a_i, \quad \forall i \in \{1,2,...,n\}, \\
& & & a_i \geq 0, \quad \forall i \in \{1,2,...,n\}.
\end{aligned}
\]

Determine under what conditions on $c_i$, $a_i$, $e_{ij}$ and $p_{ij}$ this optimization problem has a unique solution.
